The \texttt{docs/} subdirectories cover: \texttt{core/} (essential
docs), \texttt{guides/} (skill levels 1--12), \texttt{architecture/}
(system design), \texttt{usage/} (content authoring),
\texttt{operational/} (build, config, logging, troubleshooting),
\texttt{reference/} (API, FAQ, glossary), \texttt{modules/} (23
infrastructure modules), \texttt{development/} (contributing, testing),
\texttt{best-practices/} (version control, migration), \texttt{prompts/}
(21 AI prompt templates), \texttt{security/} (steganography, hashing),
and \texttt{audit/} (review reports).

Every count in this appendix is injected from live repository
introspection rather than hand-maintained: \texttt{380} counts every
Markdown file beneath \texttt{docs/} recursively, \texttt{17} counts its
first-level subdirectories, and \texttt{21} counts the workflow
subdirectories that each carry a \texttt{SKILL.md} descriptor. This is
the same discipline the manuscript argues for throughout---a hand-typed
``90+ files across 12 subdirectories'' silently rots as the tree grows,
whereas a token re-resolves on every render. A reader onboarding to the
repository should start at \texttt{docs/core/}, follow the graduated
\texttt{docs/guides/} skill ladder, and consult the per-directory
\texttt{AGENTS.md}/\texttt{README.md} pair nearest to whatever code they
are editing; AI agents additionally read each module's \texttt{SKILL.md}
to locate capabilities without guessing API signatures.
